On December 7, 2021, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. proclaimed it as National Pearl Harbor Remembrance Day. This day commemorates the attack on Pearl Harbor by the Imperial Japanese Navy in 1941, which led to the United States entering World War II. The attack resulted in the deaths of 2,403 service members and civilians. The president honors the patriots who lost their lives, recognizes the valor of those who defended the nation, and emphasizes the importance of peace and reconciliation. The president also acknowledges the sacrifices made by the Greatest Generation, who guided the country through challenging times and laid the foundations for international alliances. He urges all Americans to reflect on the courage shown by the warriors on that day and expresses gratitude to the survivors. The president calls for the flag of the United States to be flown at half-staff on December 7, 2021, in honor of those who died at Pearl Harbor.